          <ol>
            <li xml:id="exer_sec43-setdiff3a">
              <p>
                Draw two general Venn diagrams for the sets <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>,
                and <m>C</m>.
                On one, shade the region that represents <m>A - \left( {B - C} \right)</m>,
                and on the other,
                shade the region that represents <m>\left( {A - B} \right) \cup \left( A - C^c \right)</m>.
                Based on the Venn diagrams,
                make a conjecture about the relationship between the sets <m>A - \left( {B - C} \right)</m> and
                <m>\left( {A - B} \right) \cup \left( A - C^c \right)</m>. (Are the two sets equal?
                If not, is one of the sets a subset of the other set?)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove the conjecture from <xref ref="exer_sec43-setdiff3a"/>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec43-7">
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be subsets of some universal set <m>U</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>A</m> and <m>B - A</m> are disjoint sets.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>A \cup B = A \cup \left( {B - A} \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec43-8">
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be subsets of some universal set <m>U</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>A - B</m> and <m>A \cap B</m> are disjoint sets.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>A = \left( {A - B} \right) \cup \left( {A \cap B} \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be subsets of some universal set <m>U</m>.
          Prove or disprove each of the following: \end{tabular}
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A - \left(A \cap B^c \right) = A \cap B</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\left( A^c \cup B \right)^c \cap A = A - B</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\left( A \cup B \right) - A = B - A</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\left( A \cup B \right) - B = A - \left( A \cap B \right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Evaluation of proofs</em>  See the instructions for <xref ref="exer_proofeval"/> on <xref ref="exer_proofeval"></xref>
          from <xref ref="S_directproof"></xref>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>,
                and <m>C</m> are subsets of some universal set <m>U</m>,
                then <m>A - \left( B - C \right) = A - \left(B \cup C \right)</m>.
                <proof>
                  <me>
                    \begin{aligned}A - \left( B - C \right) \amp = \left(A - B \right) - \left( A - C \right) \\ \amp = \left( A \cap B^c \right) \cap \left(A \cap C^c \right) \\ \amp = A \cap \left( B^c \cap C^c\right) \\ \amp = A \cap \left( B \cup C \right)^c \\ \amp = A - \left( B \cup C \right) \end{aligned}
                  </me>
                  <p>
                    \qedhere
                  </p>
                </proof>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>,
                and <m>C</m> are subsets of some universal set <m>U</m>,
                then <m>A - \left(B \cup C \right) = \left(A - B \right) \cap \left(A - C \right)</m>.
                <proof>
                  <p>
                    We first write <m>A - \left(B \cup C \right) = A \cap \left(B \cup C \right)^c</m> and then use one of De Morgan's Laws to obtain
                    <me>
                      A - \left(B \cup C \right)= A \cap \left(B^c \cap C^c \right)
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    We now use the fact that <m>A = A \cap A</m> and obtain
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>A - \left(B \cup C \right)= A \cap A \cap B^c \cap C^c = \left(A \cap B^c \right) \cap \left(A \cap C^c \right) = \left(A - B \right) \cap \left(A - C \right)</m>.
                  </p>
                </proof>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
